        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName>5 Bertie Terrace | Leamington</placeName>
                    <date>March 31 /72</date>
                    <salute>My dear Darwin</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>Your letter will be a great encouragement to Crookes &amp; I have forwarded it to him to read, telling him what I had written.<ref target="#foot.f1"/></p>
<p>About the ‘female’—I hesitated a full 10 minutes before inserting the word ‘it’, on the ground that the subject of the story might be identified in after life &amp; that that the knowledge of the trick might damage her marrying value.!<ref target="#foot.f2"/></p>
<p>I do not know if I am over fastidious.— It is purely my own idea—no objection was raised by any of the family. So do entirely as you like.</p>
<p>Very sincerely y<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi> | Francis Galton</p> 
                </div>
            </div>

            
            
            
        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">See <ref target="./DCP-LETT-8258.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter to Francis Galton, 29 March [1872]</ref>. Galton refers to <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_1132.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">William Crookes</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">See <ref target="./DCP-LETT-8258.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter to Francis Galton, 29 March [1872]</ref> and n. 3. In his report to CD (now missing), Galton had evidently hesitated to name the sex of the grandchild mentioned in his <ref target="./DCP-LETT-4730.xml" resp="#mjhawkins" cert="high">letter of [before 28 March 1872]</ref> (<ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_7181.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Agnes Isabel Butler</ref>). The ‘trick’ was an arm movement carried out while sleeping.</note>
        </div>        
            
